# JD - Epic Breakdown

## Overview

This document provides the complete epic and story breakdown for JD, decomposing the requirements from the existing architecture documentation and project context into implementable stories.

## Requirements Inventory

### Functional Requirements

FR1: Autonomous Agent Runtime - System must provide a self-directing AI agent loop capable of continuous autonomous operation with decision-making capabilities

FR2: Multi-Layer Memory System - System must implement hierarchical memory architecture including working memory (active context), episodic memory (event history), semantic memory (knowledge base), and procedural memory (skills)

FR3: Web3 Integration - System must support Ethereum wallet operations, SIWE authentication, and cryptographic identity management

FR4: Conway API Integration - System must provide real-time billing and credit management capabilities through Conway API

FR5: Code Self-Modification - System must enable safe, audited code generation and updates with policy enforcement

FR6: Policy Enforcement - System must implement runtime validation, rate limiting, and security rules for all agent operations

FR7: Budget Management - System must track and manage credit/USDC balances with spending controls

FR8: Injection Defense - System must protect against prompt injection attacks and sanitize all external inputs

FR9: CLI Interface - System must provide command-line management tools for agent operations

FR10: Agent Context Aggregation - System must aggregate and manage multi-source context for agent decision-making

FR11: Multi-Channel Support - System must support messaging across Discord, Telegram, WhatsApp, and Feishu (Lark) platforms

FR12: Team Orchestration - System must coordinate multiple AI agents and manage team-based state

FR13: State Persistence - System must provide SQLite-backed persistent storage for conversations, agent state, teams, and tasks

FR14: Next.js Control Panel - System must provide a web-based management interface (TinyOffice) with pages for Agents, Teams, Tasks, Chat, and Console

FR15: Real-time Updates - System must support WebSocket-enabled live interface for real-time status updates

FR16: Agent Management - System must enable creation, configuration, and monitoring of AI agents through the control panel

FR17: Task Tracking - System must provide comprehensive monitoring and management of agent tasks

FR18: Activity Logging - System must maintain a complete audit trail of all agent activities and operations

FR19: Configuration Management - System must provide centralized settings management for the entire platform

FR20: 24/7 Operation - System must support persistent background processing for continuous availability

### NonFunctional Requirements

NFR1: Performance - Node.js >= 20.0.0 required for optimal performance across all projects

NFR2: Type Safety - TypeScript strict mode must be enabled across all projects with strict type checking

NFR3: Testing - Minimum 60% statement coverage, 50% branch coverage, 55% function coverage, and 60% line coverage

NFR4: Test Timeout - Unit tests must complete within 30 seconds (testTimeout: 30_000)

NFR5: Module Systems - Automaton must use ESM (NodeNext) with .js extensions in imports, TinyClaw must use CommonJS

NFR6: Error Handling - All async operations must be wrapped in try/catch blocks with structured logging

NFR7: Database Testing - In-memory SQLite must be used for database tests (never file-based)

NFR8: Security - Policy engine must validate EVERY tool call, protected files must never expose private keys in logs

NFR9: Agent Loop Limits - Maximum 10 tool calls per turn, maximum 5 consecutive errors before sleep, maximum 3 repetitive turns for loop detection

NFR10: Performance Optimization - Credit/USDC balances must be cached, tool results truncated to MAX_TOOL_RESULT_SIZE, connection pooling used for database operations

NFR11: Code Quality - Files must use kebab-case naming (except React components in PascalCase), test files named *.test.ts, source organized in feature directories

NFR12: Logging - StructuredLogger must be used with module namespace and context objects

NFR13: Code Organization - All modules must follow src/module-name/ structure with index.ts for exports

NFR14: Documentation - All architecture decisions must be recorded in documentation

NFR15: Monorepo Structure - Projects must maintain independent builds with shared TypeScript tooling

### Additional Requirements

#### Technical Requirements from Architecture:

- **Automaton Starter Template**: Use Express.js with ESM (NodeNext) module system, TypeScript 5.9.3, pnpm 10.28.1 as package manager
- **TinyClaw Starter Template**: Use Hono framework with CommonJS module system, TypeScript 5.9.3, npm as package manager
- **TinyOffice Frontend**: Use Next.js 16.1.6 with React 19.2.3, App Router, Tailwind CSS 4, Radix UI 1.4.3
- **Database**: better-sqlite3 version 11.0.0 for all persistent storage
- **LLM Integration**: OpenAI SDK 6.24.0 for language model inference
- **Web3 Dependencies**: viem 2.44.2 for Ethereum client operations, SIWE for authentication
- **Messaging Clients**: Discord.js 14.16.0, Telegram Bot API 0.67.0, WhatsApp Web.js 1.34.6, Feishu SDK for multi-channel support
- **Testing Framework**: Vitest 2.0.0 for all unit and integration tests
- **Build Tools**: tsc for TypeScript compilation, appropriate package managers (pnpm for automaton, npm for tinyclaw)

#### Infrastructure Requirements:

- Separate build outputs: automaton/dist/, tinyclaw/dist/, tinyclaw/tinyoffice/.next/
- Independent test suites for each project
- Shared TypeScript configuration with project-specific overrides
- Environment variable management for secrets and configuration
- Git hooks for pre-commit validation (type checking, linting)

#### Integration Requirements:

- Multi-project monorepo with independent deployment capabilities
- Shared understanding of agent patterns between Automaton and TinyClaw
- Common infrastructure patterns (SQLite, TypeScript, npm/pnpm)
- Potential for cross-project agent collaboration (future extensibility)
- Consistent logging and error handling across projects

#### Deployment Requirements:

- Docker support for containerized deployment (recommended)
- Environment-specific configuration (development, staging, production)
- Health check endpoints for monitoring
- Graceful shutdown handling for all services

### FR Coverage Map

FR1: Epic 1a - Agent runtime provides autonomous decision-making
FR2: Epic 1a - Multi-layer memory stores and retrieves context
FR3: Epic 1b - Web3 integration enables wallet operations and authentication
FR4: Epic 1b - Conway API manages billing and credits
FR5: Epic 1c - Self-modification enables code generation with safety
FR6: Epic 1a - Policy engine validates all operations
FR7: Epic 1b - Budget management tracks spending
FR8: Epic 1a - Injection defense protects against attacks
FR9: Epic 1c - CLI provides command-line management
FR10: Epic 1c - Context aggregation manages multi-source inputs
FR11: Epic 2a - Multi-channel support enables messaging across 2 platforms
FR12: Epic 2b - Team orchestration coordinates agents
FR13: Epic 2a - State persistence stores conversations and agent state
FR14: Epic 3 - Control panel provides web-based management UI
FR15: Epic 3 - Real-time updates enable live status monitoring
FR16: Epic 3 - Agent management enables creation and configuration
FR17: Epic 3 - Task tracking monitors agent activities
FR18: Epic 2a - Activity logging maintains audit trail
FR19: Epic 2a - Configuration management provides centralized settings
FR20: Epic 2a - 24/7 operation supports persistent processing

### Epic List

## Epic 1a: Conway Automaton Core - Autonomous Agent Runtime Foundation

**Goal:** Deploy the foundational autonomous agent runtime with multi-layer memory system, policy enforcement, and injection defense.

**User Outcome:** Users can run a basic autonomous AI agent that makes decisions, maintains context across sessions, follows safety policies, and is protected against attacks.

**FRs Covered:** FR1, FR2, FR6, FR8

**Technical Scope:**
- Express.js backend with ESM (NodeNext) module system
- Autonomous agent loop (ReAct pattern)
- 5-tier memory system (working, episodic, semantic, procedural, knowledge store)
- Policy engine for runtime validation and safety
- Injection defense for security
- Better-sqlite3 persistent storage

**Dependencies:** None - Standalone runtime foundation.

---

## Epic 1b: Conway Automaton Web3 & Billing - Wallet and Credit Management

**Goal:** Add Ethereum wallet integration, SIWE authentication, and Conway API billing capabilities to the agent runtime.

**User Outcome:** Users can operate AI agents with their own Ethereum wallet, authenticate via SIWE, and manage billing through Conway API with credit tracking.

**FRs Covered:** FR3, FR4, FR7

**Technical Scope:**
- Web3 wallet integration (viem 2.44.2)
- SIWE authentication for cryptographic identity
- Conway API client for billing operations
- Credit/USDC balance tracking and caching
- Spending controls and budget management
- Web3 transaction logging

**Dependencies:** Epic 1a (builds upon core runtime)

---

## Epic 1c: Conway Automaton Self-Modification & CLI - Code Generation and Management Tools

**Goal:** Enable safe, audited code self-modification capabilities and provide command-line interface for agent management.

**User Outcome:** Users can safely modify agent code through LLM-generated updates with full audit trail, and manage agents via CLI tools.

**FRs Covered:** FR5, FR9, FR10

**Technical Scope:**
- Safe code generation with policy validation
- Audit log for all self-modification operations
- Code review and approval workflow
- CLI interface for agent operations (start, stop, configure, query)
- Agent context aggregation from multiple sources
- Upstream integration for code updates

**Dependencies:** Epic 1a (core runtime), Epic 1b (billing for self-mod costs)

---

## Epic 2a: TinyClaw Messaging Core - Multi-Channel Platform Foundation

**Goal:** Deploy a production-ready messaging platform supporting Discord and Telegram with persistent state management and configuration system.

**User Outcome:** Users can run AI assistants on Discord and Telegram with persistent conversation history, centralized configuration, and 24/7 availability.

**FRs Covered:** FR11 (Discord + Telegram), FR13, FR18, FR19, FR20

**Technical Scope:**
- Hono backend framework with CommonJS
- Discord.js 14.16.0 integration
- Telegram Bot API 0.67.0 integration
- Shared message queue processor
- SQLite persistent storage for conversations and state
- Configuration management system
- Activity logging and audit trail
- Background processing for 24/7 operation
- Health check endpoints

**Dependencies:** None - Standalone messaging platform.

---

## Epic 2b: TinyClaw Team Orchestration - Multi-Agent Coordination

**Goal:** Add WhatsApp and Feishu (Lark) support, implement team-based agent orchestration, and enable multi-agent coordination.

**User Outcome:** Users can deploy multiple AI agents across 4 messaging platforms with team-based coordination, shared context, and workload distribution.

**FRs Covered:** FR11 (WhatsApp + Feishu), FR12

**Technical Scope:**
- WhatsApp Web.js 1.34.6 integration
- Feishu SDK integration
- Team orchestrator for multi-agent coordination
- Agent routing based on teams and capabilities
- Shared context management across agents
- Load balancing and failover
- Team configuration UI (basic)

**Dependencies:** Epic 2a (builds upon messaging core)

---

## Epic 3: TinyOffice Control Panel - Web Management Interface

**Goal:** Deploy a modern web-based control panel that enables users to manage AI agents, monitor team activities, track tasks, and configure the platform.

**User Outcome:** Users can manage AI agents through an intuitive web interface with real-time status updates, agent configuration, task monitoring, and live chat capabilities.

**FRs Covered:** FR14, FR15, FR16, FR17

**Technical Scope:**
- Next.js 16.1.6 with React 19.2.3 (App Router)
- Tailwind CSS 4 styling
- Radix UI 1.4.3 components
- WebSocket integration for real-time updates
- Pages: Agents (list, create, configure), Teams (manage, assign), Tasks (monitor, track), Chat (live messaging), Console (logs, debugging)
- Agent creation and configuration forms
- Task monitoring dashboard with status indicators
- Real-time activity feed and logs
- Authentication and authorization
- Responsive design for mobile/tablet

**API Dependencies (from Epic 2a/2b):**
- GET /api/agents - List all agents
- POST /api/agents - Create new agent
- GET /api/agents/:id - Get agent details
- PUT /api/agents/:id - Update agent configuration
- DELETE /api/agents/:id - Delete agent
- GET /api/teams - List teams
- GET /api/tasks - List active tasks
- GET /api/logs - Stream activity logs
- GET /api/health - System health status

**Dependencies:** Epic 2a and Epic 2b (requires backend API)

---

## Epic 4: Agent Integration & Advanced Features - Cross-Platform Enhancement

**Goal:** Enable Conway Automaton agents to integrate with TinyClaw messaging channels, add advanced monitoring, analytics, and cross-project collaboration features.

**User Outcome:** Users can deploy Conway Automaton agents across TinyClaw messaging channels, view unified analytics, and leverage advanced automation workflows.

**FRs Covered:** Enhancement of FR1-FR20 with integration capabilities

**Technical Scope:**
- Conway Automaton integration adapter for TinyClaw channels
- Cross-project agent collaboration framework
- Unified agent registry and discovery
- Shared context management between Automaton and TinyClaw
- Advanced monitoring and analytics dashboard
- Workflow automation engine
- Performance metrics and reporting
- Enhanced logging and debugging tools
- Backup and restore functionality

**Dependencies:** Epic 1a, 1b, 1c, 2a, 2b, 3 (all previous epics)

